<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-555-176  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 555 176.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  June 11 1990 v7 n23 p10(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Upgrade gives Gescan text retrieval system more zip. (Gescanrelease 4.0) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Slavin, Lois.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Gescan International Inc upgraded its Gescan hardware/softwaresolution for text and image handling on VAX minicomputers runningVMS by providing a search accelerator that increases processingpower by 400 percent.andP;  A direct memory access controller isincluded in the purchase price.andP;  A proprietary search algorithmlets the accelerator board add over 1,000 MIPS of text processingpower to a system.andP;  Prices for Gescan 4.0 start at $22,000 and runto $79,000, depending on the system used.andP;  It will be available inJul 1990.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Gescan International Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   GESCAN 4.0 (Data base management system) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionBoards-CardsSoftware Packages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Upgrade gives Gescan text retrieval system more zipandM;RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C.andP;  -- Gescan International has upgraded itsfull-text retrieval system, offering a search accelerator that companyofficials claim increases processing power by 400 percent over the previousversion of the system.andM;Gescan, a hardware and software offering that handles text and image,supports DEC-windows and DEC's Compound Document Architecture (CDA) with therelease of version 4.0.andM;The product runs on VAXes under VMS and requires a direct memory accesscontroller.andP;  The controller is included in the purchase price.andM;Gescan's proprietary search algorithm allows the Gescan accelerator board toadd more than 1,000 MIPS of text processing power to a user's system,according to company officials.andM;&quot;Our main objective is to provide an easy approach to documentationmanagement that will eliminate the need to index information,&quot; said DavidMorris, Gescan's vice president of planning and support.andM;&quot;The creation and maintenance of an index for full text retrieval has beendifficult for users,&quot; Morris said.andM;&quot;Our new processor off-loads CPU so more applications can be run and moreusers added without requiring a bigger computer, more disk storage, morememory, or a database administrator or system manager,&quot; he said.andM;According to users of Gescan's previous release, 3.7, the text retrievalaccelerator has proved to be an important asset.andM;Monthly savings pegged at $10,000andM;&quot;I estimate we're saving about $10,000 per month in mainframe processingcosts,&quot; said Steve DiCesare, manager of information systems at GeneralElectric's Business Information Center in Albany, N.Y.andM;&quot;We purchased the system because we wanted high-speed text informationmanagement for information gathered on our mainframe,&quot; DiCesare said.andM;&quot;Mainframe applications were cost-prohibitive, so we purchased a stand-aloneMicroVAX and Gescan 3.7 solution,&quot; DiCesare added.andM;Prices for Gescan release 4.0 start at $22,000 for a MicroVAX II to about$79,000 for a VAX 6000- or 8000-series system.andM;The product is scheduled to be available next month.andM;For additional information about Gescan release 4.0, Gescan InternationalInc. can be contacted at P.O. Box 12599, Research Triangle Park, NC 27709,(919) 460-3100.andO;</TEXT></DOC>